@bingtianbaihua By using tls sni name it is possible to use an lb to route traffic to different frp servers behind same ip and port, even if they are strict tcp by checking sni name before tls handshake.

The rationale is if you have a large kubernetes cluster with alot of frp servers and you want to expose them behind a layer 4 capable ingress. 
When its setup properly you can have as many frp servers as you want in your cluster, and expose them on the same ip and port, as long as they correspond to a unique SNI name. So there is only need for one NLB loadbalancer in aws for example. 

Most loadbalancers also have support for this functionality themselves, so its not limited to kubernetes. You can use it in normal server setups behind a loadbalancer as well.

